data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for your test:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Exact count gives better failure messages |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows "Expected: 3, Actual: 2" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent and failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(predicate)` | Add a message parameter | `"Assert.IsTrue failed"` alone is useless |

Also consider `CollectionAssert.Contains`, `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent`, and `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique` where appropriate. The main benefit is **better failure diagnostics** — `Assert.AreEqual` tells you what was expected vs. actual, while `Assert.IsTrue` just says "false".
